<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-769-815  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 769 815.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 17 1989 v6 n28 p31(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Congressional input valuable in telecom policy-setting. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pearce, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Congress and the Bush Administration, along withtelecommunications industry professionals, must work together toprovide a business environment that nurtures the construction ofinformation networks.andP;  It is incorrect to suggest that Congress'attempts to regulate and shape the information andtelecommunications markets should not be taken seriously.andO;Congress has a profound influence on public policy, wisely andexpertly uses its authority to assert control, and influencespresidential appointees who run the federal agencies, thecommittees and the courts.andP;  Congress possesses the determinationneeded to develop a legislative package to shape public policy asthis country enters the information age.andP;  The shape of thatlegislation will depend on cooperation and input Congress receivesfrom industry and consumer groups.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. CongressGovernment RegulationTelecommunicationsLegislation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>